arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase XI: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
3.65 m north south -by- 4.50 m east west.

Locus 23 is the layer of wash south of the main east west wall (Locus 25). It is a fine but compact sandy soil (Munsell 7.5 YR 4/6 strong brown), with a very high pottery content and no other significant inclusions. The unusual quantity of pottery, especially with the further high pottery content in loci below Locus 23 suggests that this may not simply be a wash layer, but could instead be purposeful dumping. This is however not clear, though a closer look at the consistency of the pottery styles and dates could help clarify this issue. The locus is phased to Stage 8, the late period of sedimentation.

Phase XIV: Modern period marked by Bedouin activity and the accumulation of recent debris. Nazzal's dump is dug between the collapsed Porch columns on the temple Forecourt. A German survey between the temple stylobate and Forecourt results in the disturbance of these deposits.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue. Upper levels of fluvial wash are deposited. Rooms A and B are abandoned.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
